BW <- read.table("BirthsKingCounty2001-Biost514-517-2022.txt", header = T)
BW$sex <- ifelse(BW$sex == "M", 1, 0) # 1 represent male, otherwise female
BW$smoker <- ifelse(BW$smoker == "Y", 1, 0) # 1 represent smoke during pregnancy, otherwise don't
BW$drinker <- ifelse(BW$drinker == "Y", 1, 0) # 1 represent drink during pregnancy, otherwise don't

library("rigr")
## rigr version 1.0.4: Regression, Inference, and General Data Analysis Tools in R
library("ggplot2")
library("knitr")
library("ggpubr")

a <- ggplot(data = BW, aes(as.character(firstep), bwt)) + geom_boxplot()
b <- ggplot(data = BW, aes(as.character(firstep), age)) + geom_boxplot()
c <- ggplot(data = BW, aes(as.character(firstep), wpre)) + geom_boxplot()
d <- ggplot(data = BW, aes(as.character(firstep), wgain)) + geom_boxplot()
ggarrange(a, b, c, d, labels = c("birthWeight", "age", "previousWeight", "weightGain"),
          ncol = 2, nrow = 2)

There are four continuous variables in the given dataset, which are age, bwt, wpre and wgain. According to table 1(descriptive statistics), the mean of the variables bwt, wpre and wgain are all deviated from their median value, which indicates that there are potential outliers for them. The following boxplots further indicates this conclution.

descrip(BW$bwt, strata = BW$firstep)
##                   N     Msng  Mean      Std Dev    Min       25%       Mdn     
## BW$bwt:  All       2500     0    3414     559.4     255.0      3096      3444  
## BW$bwt:    Str  0  2097     0    3425     548.4     255.0      3118      3459

## BW$bwt:  All         3766      5175  
## BW$bwt:    Str  0    3770      5175  
## BW$bwt:    Str  1    3742      4933
ggplot(data = BW, aes(bwt)) + geom_histogram( binwidth = 50)

The means of the birth weight for the two groups(participated or did not participate in the program) are both smaller than their medians, which indicates that there might has a left skewness. The histogram further indicates that both groups are slightly left-skewed. Women with high risk of having low birthWeight babies were encouraged to participate in this program might be one of the reasons for the skewness. They are more likely to deliever babies with low birthwight and hence cause the skewness.

BW_fs <- subset(BW, BW$firstep==1)
fs_low <- sum(BW_fs$bwt < 2500)/nrow(BW_fs); fs_very_low <- sum(BW_fs$bwt < 1500)/nrow(BW_fs)
BW_nfs <- subset(BW, BW$firstep==0)
nfs_low <- sum(BW_nfs$bwt < 2500)/nrow(BW_nfs); nfs_very_low <- sum(BW_nfs$bwt < 1500)/nrow(BW_nfs)
bw_fs <- matrix(c(fs_low, fs_very_low, nfs_low, nfs_very_low), ncol=2)
rownames(bw_fs) <- c("low", "very low"); colnames(bw_fs) <- c("fs", "nfs")
